{
  "texts": [
    "In the real world, graph data often appear in large-scale forms covering complex systems in numerous domains, such as social networks, protein interaction networks in bioinformatics, and transportation networks.",
    "Although existing graph pooling methods have achieved remarkable results on small-scale graph datasets, such as PROTEINS, DD, NCI1, etc., the high computational time and storage space requirements of these methods severely limit their applicability when facing large-scale graph data.",
    "The processing of large-scale graph data not only requires algorithms to be theoretically efficient but also needs to demonstrate good scalability in practical deployment.",
    "This means that graph pooling methods should not only be able to deal with a huge number of nodes and edges but also be able to efficiently extract the key information in the graph under limited computational resources and storage conditions.",
    "Therefore, there is an urgent need to design a new, efficient, and well-scalable graph pooling algorithm to meet the challenges posed by large-scale graph processing."
  ]
}